    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I haven't done much intercropping, they're just planted in the same bed. Could it be a lack of nitrogen though? If the bottom leaves are yellowing first, some people say that's a sign the plant is hungry. How would I actually fix the nitrogen levels in the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nitrogen deficiency is a common culprit when it comes to yellowing leaves, especially on the lower parts of the plant. It's true that some gardeners swear by the \"nitrogen test\" where the yellow leaves are the first to go, but it's not a foolproof method. \n\nTo confirm nitrogen levels, you can perform a soil test, which will give you a more accurate reading. If the test reveals a nitrogen deficiency, you can take corrective action by adding organic matter like compost or well-rotted manure to the soil. These materials are rich in nitrogen and will help replenish the soil's nutrient reserves.\n\nAnother option is to use a nitrogen-rich fertilizer, but be careful not to overdo it. Tomatoes have a relatively high nitrogen requirement, so make sure to follow the instructions on the fertilizer package and avoid burning the roots with excessive nitrogen.\n\nIt's also worth noting that nitrogen is not the only nutrient that's essential for tomato plants. Phosphorus and potassium are also crucial, and a balanced fertilizer can help ensure that your plants are getting all the nutrients they need.",
